Okay folks: we don’t usually do a set review for the Commander products, but they’re once a year and kind of a big deal, so this time we’re gonna. 

These’ll be like normal reviews, by color, not by deck (the reason being that some of these cards, like the commons, show up in multiple decks). 

We’re looking at: 
-White 
-Blue
-Black
-Red 
-Green
-Artifacts and Lands
-Gold pt. 1 (the three headliner commanders for each deck) 
-Gold pt. 2 (all remaining gold cards, including any multicolor legends outside of the deck’s main 3)

As a reminder, we’re only reviewing original cards, not every single card. You can (and probably should) take a moment to acknowledge favorite reprints, though. 

Refer to the updated style guide pinned to this channel. The Set Review section is at the bottom of the guide.

<@U3MTJRAQL>, going through the updated style guide. How do you feel about "Jxnny" and "Txmmy?" I know some major publications have used "Latinx." is an x appropriate here as well?
Strikes me as the type of thing our audience is likely to think is a typo :confused:
Maaan, fuck our audience
Just thought I'd ask, as I've seen it used and used it myself.
If I could update the names of the psychographics I would rename "Timmy" to "Sammy."
Not sure about "Johnny" or the "Melvin" aesthetic profile, though
I won’t claim to be an expert at gender identities, but I’m certainly invested in making sure we don’t put out content that alienates specific demographics
Certainly. I just like using an x instead of having to write out "Jenny/Johnny" "Timmies and Tammies" each time.
If you say something like “Timmies and Jennies” I think that’s solid
It’s just a way of being conscientious. It’s why we don’t want to always default to using “he” when describing a hypothetical player
Sure. I'm fully on board with being conscientious. One thing that "Jenny and Timmy" doesn't cover, though, is non-binary and agender folks
I guess all I can say to that is that this is also true of saying “Johnny/Jenny”
It is. Maybe it's one that WotC will address in the future.
